
git-bug is a nice tool for in-repo tracking of issues, but
it has some foibles.

Sources:
- https://github.com/git-bug/git-bug
- https://github.com/dspinellis/git-issue
- https://sciit.gitlab.io/sciit/
- https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=43971620



# Basic workflow
# Create a user (makes an object in refs/identities)
id=$(git bug user new \
	--avatar $(gh api user --jq '.avatar_url') \
	--email "${EMAIL?}" \
	--name "${UNAME?}"
)
git bug user ls              # List users
git bug user adopt ${id?}    # Adopt a user id (1)
git bug bug new              # Create a new issue
git bug termui               # Browse issues
git bug bug status:open      # List open issues
git bug bug show ${id?}      # Show comments on an issue (2)
git push ${remote?} 'refs/identities/*:refs/identities/*' 'refs/bugs/*:refs/bugs/*'

git-bug bug comment ${id?}   #

# Notes:
#  1) If you create an identity and then fetch refs from that remote in a new repo,
#     you should adopt the identity in the clone.
#  2) Yikes; 'git-bug bug show' does not give any timestamps.  But you can fetch details
#     with "git-bug bug show -f json ${id?}" and you can see the log with:
#     git log $(git for-each-ref --format='%(objectname)' "refs/bugs/${id?}*")
#     It's a pain to correlate the timestamps to the comments.  I need to write a
#     script to do that.  Or, view the issue with 'git-bug termui', but then you cannot
#     control the timestamp formats and you just see dates.  Allegedly, git-bug bug show
#     takes a --date argument, but that's not working in v0.10.1, which is most recent.



# To fetch all the issues and identities from a remote:
git fetch ${remote-origin} 'refs/bugs/*:refs/bugs/*' 'refs/identities/*:refs/identities/*'
--or--
git bug pull ${remote-origin}
